{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_adamsmorgan_ver01/data/sn84026749/0022225467A/1930021101/0885.xml":{"full_text":"2\nLOWMAN SAYS SCORE OF DISCHARGED AGENTS SPY IN D. C.\nCHIEF DISAVOWS\nCAPITOL HILL\nSNOOPERS\n(Continued from P\u00abg\u00ab\n'I\nBureau, for taking his charges\nof malfeasance in office against\ncertain officials of the Prohibition\nBureau to Senator Borah and\nether acts of insubordination.\nThe Wheeler resolution calling\nfor a complete and sweeping\ngat the administration of pro\njn by the Prohibition Bureau\nwas before the Senate Judi-\nCommittee. A poll of many\nntial members of the Sen-\nSunday by the New York\n\u2019Herald-Tribune, it is said, showed\nJan overwhelming sentiment in\n\u2019favor of the Wheeler resolution.\nWhile charges made by Flynn\n'against John F. J. Herbert, former\n\u2022\u25a0prohibition administrator of the\niMaryland-District of Columbia dis\nitrtct but now technically in charge\ntof .the Montana-Idaho district,\n\u2022brought the Wheeler resolution to\n\u25a0a head, the measure seeks to get\nfat the fundamental cause of the\nof prohibition enforce\n*ment all over the country.\nBroad Inquiry Planned\nIf authorized, the investigation\nWill be broader than anything ever\nbefore undertaken in probing pro\nhibition enforcement. It will go\nright to the heart of the prohibi\ntion enforcement service itself,\nsince it calls for Investigation of\nall charges of corruption, ineffi\nciency and the like, and will seek\nto determine whether this is the\ncause of the breakdown of prohi\nbition enforcement or whether, as\nthe wets claim, the \u201claw is uni\nversally unpopular.\u201d\nEarly action on the Wheeler\nresolution was forecast today by\nSenator George W. Norris of Ne\nbraska, chairman of the Judiciary\nCommittee, who announced that\nthe resolution would be given\nright of way by the committee\nnext Monday.\nSenator Norris declined to pre\ndict what the committee\u2019s action\nwould be, but indications were\nIt not only would be reported\nfavorably but would easily pass\nthe Senate.\nThe \u201cwets\u201d in the Senate were\nopenly pleased. Senator David I.\nWalsh of Massachusetts declared\nit was \u201can epoch-making event\u201d\nwhen a dry asked for a probe of\nthe. Prohibition Buteau.\n\u201cDry\u201d leaders were rather silent\nabout their attitude, except Sena\ntor Sheppard of Texas, who de\nclared that, while the \u201cdrys\u201d do\nnot fear an inquiry, he personally\nfelt it unnecessary.\nStorm of Criticism\nThreatens to Upset\nJuryless Trial Bill\nHaving encountered wide\nspread opposition to the Wicker\nsham law enforcement commis\nsion\u2019s proposed revision of Fed\neral court procedure to strengthen\nprohibition enforcement, the\nChristopherson House Judiciary\nsubcommittee met behind closed\ndoors today to begin revision of\nthe measures.\nWith the court measures now\nheading the House calendar of\nprohibition reforms asked by\nPresident Hoover and his com\nmission, every effort will be made\nto reconcile conflicting elements\nand pave the way for early pas\nsage of the bills.\nTwo lesser bills have been\nadded to the committee\u2019s court\nmeasures by Representative Chris\ntopherson (R.) of South Dakota,\nchairman of the subcominittee at\nthe request of the commission.\nOne permits service by publica\ntion in padlock injunction cases\nif the owner of a building is\napparently evading service and\nthe second would give State,\ncounty and municipal officers the\nfight to make arrests for viola\ntion of the prohibition laws and\nCarry the cases into the Federal\ncourts.\nThe latter bill, Christopherson\nsaid, would permit the bringing\nof cases by State officers in Fed\neral courts in States, such as\nNew York, which do not have a\nState enforcement act, and in\nlocalities where opposition to pro\nhibition is so pronounced that\nlocal juries will not convict.\nThe principal court revision\nbills\u2014the juryless trials proceed\nings before United States com\nmissioner and creation of a class\nof minor offenders\u2014were ex\npected to undergo the pruning\nknife in the subcommittee.\nOld National Furniture\nGoes on Auction Today\nAuctioning of the furniture of\nthe old National Hotel, which is\nto be razed to make way for the\nFederal building program, was\nresumed at 9:30 a. m. today by\nAdam A. Weschler, auctioneer,\nand will continue until all the\nfurniture is sold.\nYesterday\u2019s auction at the\nfamous old hostelry drew crowds\nof bargain hunters. The room\nin which Henry Clay died 75\nyears ago is open for inspection\nand contains several Interesting\narticles. Booth\u2019s room is also on\ndisplay, as well as suites occu\npied by nearly every President of\nthe United States from the Civil\nWar until 1880.\n\u2019Timr* Real Estate Ad*.\nwhen purehaalnr a home take ad\nvaatace of the oaee la locating throogh\nI It\u2019s Definitely Off!\naiiwwir-a\nMi\u00ae** F\n-J\nB JB\na\n\u25a0TFPII LIB\n'JFt,'' A\nt\nBL/ y .X X M X\nX .Xfa v,\nIk*/ P\nBBK*VHB Bi I\nI i r\"\nBi\n-4\nCLARA AND HARRY RICHMAN\nFRIENDS OF CLARA BOW, the \u201cit\u201d lady of the film\nworld, quote the flaming screen celebrity as being mind\nmade-up not to marry Harry Richman\u2014today, tomorrow\nor ever. At last reports, the marriage was to have occurred\nNew Year Day and everybody knows that was far\nfetched.\nEDISON OKAYS\n5-DAY WEEK\n(Continued from Page J.)\nwaited patiently. He answered\nthe questions at the rate of one\na minute.\n\"In your opinion when will tele\nvision be practical for the home?\u201d\nwas one question.\n\u201cSome day,\u201d was Edisons\nevasive answer.\n\u201cWhat age do you consider\nelectrical development in*today\u2014\nchildhood, adolescence, maturity\nor old age?\u201d was another ques\ntion.\n\u201cChildhood,\u201d was the one word\nanswer.\nHe smiled a bit as he wrote his\nanswer to this question: \"Can you\ntell us of the greatest disappoint\nment you encountered in your\nwork: also the greatest satisfac\ntion?\u201d\n\u201cI am always disappointed until\na problem is solved,\u201d he replied.\n\u201cNot more than one out of 20 of\nthe details work at first.\u201d\nLike a Drug Store\nIn Edison\u2019s office were many\nevidences of his research work.\nOn shelves were piles of mysteri\nous looking bottles. The place\nhad the atmosphere of a drug\nstore.\nAviation he touched on lightly.\nAsk what his attitude toward\ncommercial aviation, he replied:\n\u201cDo more experimenting to in\ncrease safety before commercializ\ning too much.\u201d\n\u201cDo you think a young man\ngraduated from high school would\nderive greater benefit by spend\ning four years at the average\nmodern university or by entering\nbusiness immediately?\u201d he was\nasked.\n\u201cThe way things are today. I\nshould say enter business,\u201d was\nEdison\u2019s reply.\nWoman Quits D.A.R.\nAs Militaristic\nNEW YORK, Feb. 11 (1.N.5.).\u2014\nAnother furore shook the ranks\nof the Daughters of the American\nRevolution today with the resig\nnation of Dr. Vaerlia H. Parker,\none of America\u2019s most prominent\nwomen in the fields of social ser\nvice and education.\nIp submitting her resignation\nDr. Parker charged that organiza\ntion with attempting to block\nworld peace by supporting large\narmament programs and with un\njustified antagonism to ither\nprominent women\u2019s organizations\nbecause of the disarmament move\nment.\nDr. Parker also stated the D.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nEDITOR IN DRIVE\nON DOT LAW\nHoward L. Scott, editor of the\nKeystone News of Harrisburg,\nPa., and initiator of a referendum\nfor repeal of the prohibition\namendment in his home State,\nwill appear before the House\nJudiciary Committee tomorrow\nmorning to lay before that body\nhis reasons for a nation wide\nreferendum on the subject.\nIn four small cities in Pennsyl\nvania the names of more than\n35,000 persons have been pro\ncured who favor modification of\nthe amendment which would leg\nalize 2% per cent beer.\nFollowing his appearance be\nfore the committee, Scott intends\nto go into Ohio, the larger cities\nof Pennsylvania and New Jersey,\nwhere he will circulate his peti\ntions.\nThe petition reads as follows:\n\u201cShould both bodies of the\nPennsylvania general assembly,\nthe State senate, the house of\nrepresentatives, and the Pennsyl\nvania Representatives in Congress,\nbe requested to support a consti\ntutional amendment to repeal the\nEighteenth Amendment to the\nConstitution'of the United States,\nknown as the prohibiion amend\nment.\u201d\nIn making clear his own posi\ntion in regard to prohibition.\nScott emphasizes the fact that\nhe stands first, last and always\nfor temperance as prohibition de\nnies freedom of choice giving\nothers the authority to decide\nfor you.\nMrs. Arthur Christie\nWins Divorce in Paris\nPARIS. Feb. 11 (I.N.S.).\u2014A di\nvorce was granted here today to\nMrs. Arthur Read Christie, the\nformer Germaine Bcaume.\nShe was married in Baltimore\non January 20. 1920. She charged\ndesertion.\nA. R. was controlled by persons\nnot in sympathy with \u201cthat lib\nerty of thought and action for\nwhich the American revolutionists\nfought and bled.\u201d\nDr. Parker\u2019s letter of resigna\ntion revived the sensation caused\ntwo years ago when it was charged\nthe D. A. R had circulated\n\"blacklists\u201d of \u201cdisloyal citizens,\u201d\nfor she again charged the or\nganization with \u201cmistaken pol\nicies\u201d and denounced its alleged\n\u201cblacklists.\u201d She said denial of\nthe \u201ccirculalion of the blacklists\nin the face of generally known\nfacts caused her to lack confi\ndence in the organization.\u201d\nABOLITION OF\nSUBMARINES\nURGED\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nmethods of attack which civilized\nnations regard with horror.\u201d\nAsks Complete Abolition\nAdmitting that in the last war\nBritain had found it impossible to\nmaintain submarines in defensive\npositions solely, he pnt forward\nan unqualified demand for their\ncomplete abolition, stating that\nthey constituted a definite men\nace even to the health and safety\nof the crews which operate them.\nSpeaking on behalf of the\nUnited States, Secretary of State\nHenry L. Stimson then put for\nward an urgent plea for subma\nrine abolition, leaving no alterna\ntive to removing undersea craft\nentirely from the fleets of the\nworld.\nDenying the contention that sub\nmarines were purely defensive\naims, he declared that to sanc\ntion their use would be a \u201ccon\ntradiction of the purposes for\nwhich we have met.\u201d\n\u201cThe essential objection of the\nsubmarine,\u201d he said, \"is that it\nis a weapon particularly suscep\ntible to abuse, that it is suscep\ntible of use against merchant\nships in away that violates alike\nthe laws of war and the dictates\nof humanity.\u201d\nUse In Last War Cited\nSubmarines during the last\nwar. the, American chief dele\ngate declared, \u201crevolted the con\nscience of the world.\u201d and were\ndirectly responsible for having\nforced the United States into the\nconflict.\nStimson\u2019s speech was a severe\nindictment of the subsea craft.\n\u201cThe argument that the sub\nmarine is a purely defensive\nweapon,\u201d he said, \u201cseems to us\ndifficult to reconcile with the of\nfensive, use which has been made\nof it at great distances from its\nhome ports.\u201d\nHigh Costs Pointed Ont\nHe declared the contention that\nthe submarine is a less costly\nweapon affording a maximum of\nstrategic value for a minimum\noutlay, must be considered in the\nlight of the knowledge \u201cthat ton\nfor ton submarine is more costly\nthan any type cf surface craft and\ntwice as costly as the largest ships\nof war.\"\nConstruction and maintenance\nof the submarine, he said, will im\npose on all navies higher levels in\nthe catr which must be used\ntv combat the undersea craft\u2014\ntne destroyer and light cruiser.\n\u201cWe cannot but feel that for\nthis conference, called under such\ninfluences (the Kellogg Briand\npact) t j st Jon an instrument\nof war, the abuses of which were\ndirectly responsible for calling the\nWestern world into the greatest\nEuropean war of history, would\nbe a contradiction of the purposes\nfor which we have met.\n\u201cI am not speaking of theory\nI am peaking of historical fact\nand a fact which human ex\nperience shows is likely to be\nrepeated.\n\u201cThe essential objection to the\nsubmarine is that it is a weapon\nparticularly susceptible to abuse\nthat it is susceptible of use\nagainst merchant shipc in away\nthat violates alike the laws of\nwar and the dictates of humanity.\n\u201cThese considerations convince\nus that technical arguments\nshould be set aside in order that\nthe submarine may henceforth\nbe abolished.\u201d\nDIRECTORS TO MEET\nHYATTSVILLE, Feb. 11.\u2014Th\nregular semi-monthly meeting of\nthe Board of Directors of the\nPrince Georges Bank will be held\nat the bank next Tuesday.\nNew Dry Chief?\nk 1\n\u2014Photo by Underwood Underwood\nALF OFTEDAL\nWHEN THE prohibition forces\ngo over to the Department of\nJustice, Alf Oftedal. prominen*\nin California politics will be\nthe national dry chief, accord\ning to the San Francisco Ex\naminer.\nTha Hetited Deity\nPEOPLE\nWho Interest\nYou and\nthe Things\nThey Do\nBrookhart Attacks Grundy\nAt Phila. Labor Meeting\nPHILADELPHIA. Feb. 11.\u2014\n(I.N.S.).\u2014U. 8. Senator Smith\nW. Brookhart, of lowa, urged\nthe smashing of the banking\ngroups and launched an attack\non Senator Joseph R. Grundy\nip an address here before a\nlabor meeting.\nSenator Brookhart advocated\nfl\nken. brookhakt only nation in\nthe civilized world that by law\nprohibits the farmer and the\nlaborer from conducting any\nco-operative banking business.\"\nAlma Rubent, Well Again,\nIn N. Y. Seeking Job\nNEW YORK. Feb. 11 (I.NJS.).\nAlma Rubens, apparently recov\nered and eager to resume her\nwork in the movies or on the\nstage, Is here\ntoday.\nI feel\ngrand,\u201d she\nsaid, as she\narrived from\nthe West. \"I\nhave found\nduring my\nlong illness,\nthat this\nworld is a\ngreat place to\nlive in. I\u2019ve\nfought a hard\nbattle and I\nowe my vic-\ntory tO the ALMA Kt HENS\nfriends, many I never knew I\nhad.\u201d\nIn New York Miss Rubens\nplans to see Sam Harris about\na role in one of his productions.\nLamont Sees Nothing\nDisturbing to Business\nSecretary of Commerce\nR. P. Lamont said today that\nthere is nothing disturbing in\nthe country\u2019s business outlook\nEmployment conditions are\nImproving, the future of the\nconstruction industry was hope\nful and steel mills were oper\nating 80 per cent, according to\ny B\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0l Russia is on\nsec. i.amont a food ration\nbasis and is not expected to\nexport wheat this year.\nReports from Detroit, head\nquarters of the automobile in\ndustry, indicated that conditions\nthere were improving.\nciosiJY fight\nTO CONTINUE\n(Continued from Pago 1.)\nHeights Citizens Association, last\nnight gave it\u2019s hear' indorse\nlent vO General Crosby.\nSecretary of War Patrick Hur\nley, yesterday issuec* a lengthy\nstatement in declared\nthat, claims, of local organiza\ntions not .withstanding. General\nCrosby will automatically attain\na .civilian status following his re\ntirement arch 21.\nPlan Campaign\nMembers of the organizations\nwho will attend the meeting\ncalled by Murphy are prepared\nto wage an intensive campaign\nagainst the appointment of Gen\neral Crosby.\nThe view is taken by the\nmajority that General Crosby\nwill belong to the army despite\nclaims of the War Secretary and\nthat his appointment will there\nfore be in violation of the\norganic act. In this connection\nit is also understood that the\nJones bill which would make out\nsiders eligible for appointment to\nthe Board of Commissioners is to\ncome in for it\u2019s share of criticism\nand opposition.\nPresident Hoover remains ada\nmant and the fight probably will\nbe wagsd in the Senate.\nDespite this statement issued\nat the White House today, offi\ncials of business and civic organi\nzations in Washington were going\nahead with their plans for a meet\ning Wednesday afternoon to dis\ncuss what measures of protest\nshould be made to the President.\nsupport for a\nProgressive\nLeague labor\u2019\nparty.\n\u201cBreak the\npower of the\ngreat banking\ngroups by a\nfarmer coali\ntion,\u201d urged\nthe lowa Sen\nator.\n\u201cDo y 0 u\nrealize what\nis happening\nin America?\n\u201cIt is the\n\u2022\u2022x-s W\na survey just\ncompleted by\nthe C o m\nmerce Depart\nment.\nLamont said\nmany queries\nhad reached\nthe Com\nmerce De\npartment rel\native to the\nRussian grain\nsituation. Ac\ncording to his\ni n f ormation\nTUESDAY, FEBRUARY 11, l\u00a9Bo\nFETE TO GLDSE\n1930 CAMPAIGN\nFOB CREST\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nup\u201d campaign which has been\nunder way since last Thursday\nnight and which has as its object\nthe raising of approximately\n$300,000, if the Chest quota is to\nbe completed. The meeting will\nbe called to order at 8 o\u2019clock\nby John Poole, campaign chair\nman, and is scheduled to adjourn\nat, 10 o\u2019clock.\nReports from a' sections of the\ncity this morning indicated that\nevery unit connected with the\nChest campaign was actively at\nwork. In the mean time gifts\nwere still being received by mail\nand by telephone and the large\nnumber of pledges from the\ngovernment department, which\nwere expected to be the vanguard\nof a veritable avalanche of\nsuch pledges before the day\nwas out, were being received at\nChest headquarters. Members of\nthe Junior League were again\nsoliciting for funds at leading\nstores and banks, and all the\nbanks of the city were cooperat\ning by accepting pledges through\nspecial \u201cCommunity Chest tellers\u201d\nlocated at each bank.\nWhether today\u2019s whirlwind cam\npaign would result in reaching\nthe final quota of the chest was\nstill in doubt by chest officials,\nbut they had definitely decided\nthat the campaign will close of\nficially tonight. It was stated,\nhowever, that if the quota is not\nreached, steps will be taken to\ncontinue ttie solicitation of those\nwho have not given to the chest,\nwith the object of completing, the\nquota in this manner.\nEvery Cent Needed\n\u201cWe are not asking for one\npenny that is not needed,\u201d John\nPoole, campaign chairman, said\ntoday. \u201cEvery dollar of the sl.-\n786,737.07 sought for the chest\nhas been definitely allocated to\nsome organization by a level\nheaded, close-questioning group\nof business men and women who\ninvestigated every cent sought by\neach organization before giving It\ntheir final approval. This means\nthat we simply must have the\namount sought, and I am still\ncertain that Washington will not\nlet as worthy a project as the\nCommunity Chest fail.\u201d\nTonight's meeting will open\nwith a concert by the United\nStates Marine Band. After the\ninvocation by Rabbi W. F. Rosen\nblum, of the Washington Hebrew\nCongregation, William Schmucker\nwill lead the audience in com\nmunity singing. This will be fol\nlowed by an address by the Rt.\nRev. James E. Freeman, Episcopal\nBishop of Washington.\nGeorge O\u2019Connor and Matt\nHom, two of Washington\u2019s most\npopular entertainers, will give a\nprogram of songs which will be\nfollowed by addresses by Msgr\nP. C. Gavin, pastor of Sacred\nHeart Church, and Dr. Mordecai\nJohnson, president of Howard\nUniversity.\nFred East, baritone, will sing.\nUnit Chairmen Report\nReport of the final result of\nthe campaign will be made by\nthe unit chairmen. Merritt O.\nChance, chairman of the metro\npolitan unit, will report by regions\nas follows:\nGraham Powell, acting for\n?lmon Lyon, chairman of Region\nH. L. Hunt, jr\u201e chairman of\nRegion 2: Radford Moses, chair\nman of Region 3; James E. Col\nliflower, chairman of Region 4;\nDr. Kelly Miller, chairman 'oi\nRegion 5.\nFrank R. Jelleff. chairman of\nthe group solicitation unit, and\nNewbold Noyes, chairman of the\nspecial gifts committee, will re\nport for their respective units,\nand E. W. Libby will report re\nsults from the Government de\npartments.\nFrederic A. Delano, president of\nthe Community Chest, will speak\non \u201cOur Community\u201d; John Poole,\ncampaign chairman, on \u201cWhat\nWe Have Done.\u201d and Elwood\nStreet, director of the chest, on\n\u201cWhat We Shall Do.\u201d Tonight\u2019s\nmeeting is open to the public.\nThe workers will sit in sections\nof the hall designated by signs\nand seating charts and guests will\noccupy the balcony.\nIt is hoped that the night\u2019s\nmeeting will be the greatest gath\nering tn a charitable cause ever\nheld in Washington.\nGUILD TO SERvFdINNER\nLAUREL. Feb. 11.\u2014A turkey\ndinner will be served by the par\nish guild of St. Philip\u2019s Episcopal\nChurch, Thursday, from 5 to 9\nNext Free Diet Clinic\nFor Followers of The Washington Times*\nRevised 18-Day Hollywood Diet\nTo Be Held Thursday\nRoom 408, Hearst Building\n1319 H Street N. W.\n3:30 to 6 P. M. (Note change in hours)\nDieters and prospective dieters are invited to call\nto be weighed and to receive free medical advice on\nreducing or increasing their weight.\nAfter the Big Bite!\nw\nr A Ik\nI bl\n*'*4. wf' \"B\nBL\nBk. a v\nfIL. fl 1\nBvi\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0BBBBBBMBBr\n\u2014Time* Staff Photo\nLOUIS LANCASTER AND \u201cCOLLIE BOY.\u201d\n\u201cCOLLIE BOY\u201d is the pet of the Lancaster family,\nthe 2200 block G St. N. W., and particularly of Louis,\naged 8. Yesterday, friendship was abrogated for the\nmoment and the canine gave Louis an ugle face bite,\nfor which he received treatment at Emergency Hospital.\nNow all is forgotten. He and \u201cCollie Boy\u201d are good\npals once more.\nHUGHES TO BE\nCONFIRMED\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nmulti-millianolre oil and utflity\nmagnate appeared to have gath\nered but few converts. An >ver\nwhelming majority of the Senate,\nwhile not particularly friendly to\nHughes, will favor his confirma\ntion because of his brilliance and\nhis great success at the bar. Un\nless something unforeseen occurs,\nhe will be overwhelmingly con\nfirmed when his nomination\nreaches a vote.\nBoth Norris and Doherty paid\ntribute to his legal brilliance\nThey attacked his appointment\non a different ground. Doherty\nsaid Hughes was \u201cprejudiced on\nmany great questions and de\nclared his appointment was engi\nneered by a \u201cpolitical clique\u201d\nthat sought to rule the country.\nNorris said his appointment war\na \u201cpolitical football\u201d which de\ntracted from the high ideats of\nthe Supreme Court. He tJded\nthat no man who resigns f rom\nthe Supreme Court to seek po\nlitical and financials gains should\never be reappointed.\n\u201cSuch a procedure must in\nevitably encourage and stimulate\npolitical activity on the part of\nthe Supreme Court,\" said Norris.\n\u201cCarried to its logical conclusion,\nit will mean that judges who de\nsire to follow the course pursued\nby Mr. Hughes will be influenced\nco disregard justice in rendering\ntheir decisions and cater to the\nwish of politicians in power in\nthe political world.\u201d\nThe Senate Judiciary Commit\ntee, after hearing Norris\u2019 objection\nand a long protest from Doherty,\napproved the appointment by a\n1? to 2 vote,\nVirginia Society Plans\nColonial Pageant Feb. 24\nPlans are being made for the\nannual colonial pageant of the\nVirginia Society on February 24.\nA meeting of the executive com\nmittee of the society was held\nlast night at the Willard Hotel\nto discuss the ball. Tnis year it\nwill be a costume affair,\nSchool for Parrots\nClosed By \u201cFever\u201d\nBROWNSVILLE, Tex., Feb. 11\n(IN.S.).\u2014Psittachosis and the\nUnited States\u2019 resultant embargo\nFLORIDA LIKES\nCOOLIDGES\n(Continued from Page t.)\ntie shopping. The other day she\nwent into a grocery store which\nhappened to be crowded. Not\nwaited on for some time she\nstrolled out.* Someone recognized\nher. An employe rushed out with\nan explanation of how busy they\nwere, but she only smiled. She\nhadn\u2019t minded it a bit.\nMrs. Coolidge has a real sense\nof humor, as evidenced bv a\nstory they tell here. The other\nday, accompanied by a woman\nfriend or two. she went to Day\ntona. A girl reporter managed to\ncatch up with her. but wasn't\nsure she had the right party.\nAdmits Resemblance\n\u201cYou look a great deal like Mrs.\nCoolidge.\u201d the girl reporter said\n\u201cYes, I\u2019ve been taken for Mrs.\nCoolidge a number of times.\u201d\nMrs. Coolidge replied with a dis\narming smile.\nThe girl reporter departed\nsomewhat nonplussed.\nMrs. Coolidge prefers to remain\nout of the limelight. On the oc\ncasion when she dedicated the\nCyprus tree she willingly posed\nfor a picture but it was more\nfor \u201cthe good of the cause\u201d than\nby inclination. Like her illustrious\nhusband, she is very modest.\nCoolidge, too, is often seen in\nthe village. Hardly a day passes\nthat he does not long hike\nthrough the streets by himself.\nHe nods to passersby who recog\nnize him and occasionally stops\nto speak.\nMakes Hit With Barber\nThe village barber got the kick\nof his life the other day when\nCoolidge came in for a hair cut.\n\u201cA fine, quiet gentleman,\u201d was\nthe barber\u2019s verdict. \u201cVery little\nto say, just said: \u2018Not too much\noff the back.\u2019\nThe negro who operates the\nbarber shop shoe shine is still\ntalking of how he had the honor\nof polishing the former Presi\ndent\u2019s boots. He never thought\nhe\u2019d get a \u201cbreak\u201d like that.\non the importation of parrots\nmay result in the closing of what\nIs probably this country\u2019s only\n\u201cparrot college.\u201d\nEstablished years ago, the \u201ccol\nlege\u201d was the schooling place for\nthousands of parrots brought in\nfrom Mexico each year. In its\n\u201cclassrooms\u201d the young birds\nlearned their words and phrases,\nchiefly from phonograph records\nwhich ground out continual\nstrings of the things parrots\nshould memorize.\nW. A. (\u201cSnake\u201d) King, owner\nand operator of the institution,\ndeclares that Mexican parrots,\nthe only kind he Imports, are not\nsubject to psittachosis\u2014but a lot\nof good the assertion does him.\nHe sees a dark future for the\nparrot business.\nBrownsville has been one of\nthe largest parrot importing\npoint* in the United State*.","height":"30035","width":"23652"}}
